<Base
  title="Minimum Viable Data — Eidos AGI"
  description="Not the smallest product you can ship. The smallest data you can define. Products get replaced. Data compounds."
>
    <article class="prose-page">
      <header class="page-hero">
        <h1>Minimum Viable Data</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Not the smallest product. The smallest data.</p>
      </header>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p>The startup world asks: what's the minimum viable product? What's the smallest thing we can build and ship?</p>
        <p>That question assumes the product is the value. Build an app. Ship a feature. Deploy a service. The product is the deliverable.</p>
        <p>But products are implementations. Implementations get replaced. The React app gets rewritten in Swift. The Python service gets rewritten in Rust. The CLI gets replaced by a GUI gets replaced by a voice interface. Every product is temporary.</p>
        <p><strong>Data is the specification. Specifications compound.</strong></p>
        <p>The right question isn't "what's the smallest product we can ship?" It's: <strong>what's the smallest structured dataset that lets any AI — current or future — do the job?</strong></p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>A grocery order with no product</h2>
        <p>A GitHub repo. No software. No database. No code of any kind.</p>
        <pre><code>reeves-grocery/
  contracts/
    shopping-list.schema.json
    meal-plan.schema.json
    pantry-update.schema.json
  preferences/
    dietary.yaml
    cooking.yaml
    shopping.yaml
    household.yaml
    goals.yaml
  pantry/
    current.md
    reserve.md</code></pre>
        <p>Three schemas. Five preference files. Two pantry files. An AI reads them and orders groceries. Every week. No app, no API, no deployment, no infrastructure.</p>
        <p>That's the MVD. 372 lines of structured data. Zero lines of code.</p>
        <p>The "product" is whatever AI agent happens to read the data this week. Last month it was Claude Code. This week it's Perplexity Computer. Next month it might be something that doesn't exist yet. The product changed three times. The data changed zero times.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Products are dead</h2>
        <p>Products are code. Code is a liability. You maintain it in exchange for results — but the results are what people actually pay for, not the code.</p>
        <p>Nobody pays for a grocery ordering app. They pay for groceries showing up. Nobody pays for a deployment pipeline. They pay for services running. The product was always just the middleman between intent and result. AI removes the middleman.</p>
        <p>When you research the data — the contracts, the preferences, the state — you're defining the results directly. No code in between. No product to maintain. No middleman to break. The specification <em>is</em> the thing. Any AI reads it and produces the results.</p>

        <div class="mvd-compare">
          <div class="mvd-compare-item mvd-product">
            <div class="mvd-compare-header">Product (MVP)</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Code that does the thing</li>
              <li>Dependencies to maintain</li>
              <li>Deployment to manage</li>
              <li>Breaks when the model changes</li>
              <li>Breaks when the platform changes</li>
              <li>One AI agent can use it</li>
              <li>Gets replaced every 2 years</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="mvd-compare-item mvd-data">
            <div class="mvd-compare-header">Data (MVD)</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Schemas that define what "done" looks like</li>
              <li>Preferences that define who you are</li>
              <li>State that defines where things stand</li>
              <li>Gets more valuable as models improve</li>
              <li>Works with any AI, any platform</li>
              <li>Every agent can use it</li>
              <li>Never needs replacing</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The evidence</h2>

        <div class="mvd-evidence">
          <div class="mvd-evidence-item">
            <h3>The bitter lesson</h3>
            <p>Richard Sutton proved that general methods leveraging computation always beat hand-crafted human knowledge as compute scales. AlphaGo Zero — trained with zero human chess knowledge — destroyed Stockfish, the culmination of decades of hand-tuned expertise. Skills files are hand-crafted knowledge. Contracts are the general method.</p>
            <cite>Sutton, "The Bitter Lesson" (2019). Confirmed across chess, Go, speech, and 20 years of computer vision research.</cite>
          </div>
          <div class="mvd-evidence-item">
            <h3>Data-centric AI</h3>
            <p>Andrew Ng's research shows improving data quality is more effective than improving models. In one study, the model-centric approach failed to improve accuracy while the data-centric approach boosted it by 16%. Ng argues: "all that progress in algorithms means it's actually time to spend more time on the data." MVD is this argument taken to its conclusion: the data is where the value is.</p>
            <cite>Ng, IEEE Spectrum; MIT Sloan; Nature Scientific Reports (2024).</cite>
          </div>
          <div class="mvd-evidence-item">
            <h3>Code as liability</h3>
            <p>AI now writes 30% of Microsoft's code and over 25% of Google's. Anthropic's 2026 report shows agents building entire applications over days — creating code faster than humans can audit. The industry's response to too much code is more code (agents reviewing agents). MVD breaks the cycle: eliminate the code layer where structured data suffices.</p>
            <cite>MIT Technology Review, "10 Breakthrough Technologies 2026"; Anthropic, "Agentic Coding Trends Report 2026".</cite>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The pattern</h2>
        <p>Every MVD has three parts:</p>
        <ol class="mvd-parts">
          <li><strong>Contracts</strong> — JSON Schemas that define what valid output looks like. The shopping list contract says what a grocery order must contain. The deployment contract says what "deployed" means. The contract is the goal with structure.</li>
          <li><strong>Preferences</strong> — YAML or markdown files that define who the user is. Dietary restrictions, budget, cooking skill, brand preferences. These are stable — a person's diet doesn't change weekly.</li>
          <li><strong>State</strong> — What's true right now. What's in the pantry. What was ordered last week. What's in stock. This changes often but the format doesn't.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Contracts + preferences + state. That's the MVD. An AI reads all three and produces results. No product required.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Code is the transition layer</h2>
        <p>Some things still need code today. A Mac app that records your voice. A daemon that classifies it. But that code is a transition layer — it exists because today's AI can't yet do everything from data alone. As AI improves, the code shrinks. The data stays.</p>
        <p>The recording bucket with its JSON Schema contract will outlive the Mac app that writes it. The grocery preferences will outlive every grocery ordering app ever built. The data is the road. The code is the car. Cars get replaced. Roads last for centuries.</p>
        <p>Invest in roads.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Start with MVD</h2>
        <p>Before writing code, ask:</p>
        <ol class="mvd-steps">
          <li>What does "done" look like? Write the contract.</li>
          <li>Who is this for? Write the preferences.</li>
          <li>What's true right now? Capture the state.</li>
          <li>Can an AI produce results from just these files?</li>
          <li>If yes — you have your MVD. Ship the data. The product can come later.</li>
          <li>If no — what's missing from the data? Add it. Don't add code.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p class="mvd-closing">Minimum Viable Product asks how little code you can write. Minimum Viable Data asks how little data you need to define the results you want. One is a liability you maintain. The other is an asset that compounds. Research the data. Let AI deliver the results.</p>
      </section>

